Welcome back to segment 4.2
<i>Navigating the funding universe</i>.

2
00:00:14,032 --> 00:00:17,046
Today we are going to talk about
different types of funding,

3
00:00:17,046 --> 00:00:19,441
we are going to talk about
the stages of funding,

4
00:00:19,441 --> 00:00:22,200
the types of financing,
different kinds of investors,

5
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:25,490
and sales or exits of your business.

6
00:00:26,043 --> 00:00:29,920
Let's talk about the stages
of financing for your venture.

7
00:00:30,882 --> 00:00:34,797
We've previously discussed
the timeline of your investment

8
00:00:34,797 --> 00:00:37,493
and how much money you will need,
that was in the last segment.

9
00:00:37,643 --> 00:00:40,905
Now, we are going to look at this graphic,
which is from the last time,

10
00:00:40,905 --> 00:00:43,135
and we are going to see

11
00:00:43,135 --> 00:00:46,895
when different types of financing
are most appropriate.

12
00:00:47,260 --> 00:00:49,092
What we have covered last time,

13
00:00:49,092 --> 00:00:53,955
was the seed financing
versus the expansion financing.

14
00:00:53,955 --> 00:00:56,414
But that can be further subdivided.

15
00:00:57,384 --> 00:01:01,787
So, in this graph, you'll see
more or less seed financing,

16
00:01:02,980 --> 00:01:08,914
and seed financing might be divided
into different categories.

17
00:01:09,347 --> 00:01:12,533
And then, there could be different 
rounds of financing over time.

18
00:01:14,183 --> 00:01:18,581
Usually, we consider
the first round of financing

19
00:01:18,581 --> 00:01:22,192
where equity is given up,
where partial ownership

20
00:01:22,192 --> 00:01:24,101
- we'll talk about that more
in a few minutes -

21
00:01:24,101 --> 00:01:27,433
We called that
the series A financing.

22
00:01:30,418 --> 00:01:32,940
And then, as expansion financing kicks in,

23
00:01:33,193 --> 00:01:36,731
we would collect more rounds,
we'll have more rounds of financing,

24
00:01:36,731 --> 00:01:40,388
and we would call that
the B round or the C round.

25
00:01:40,388 --> 00:01:43,011
So, every time we have more financing

26
00:01:44,561 --> 00:01:47,802
we have additional letter
of the alphabet.

27
00:01:48,793 --> 00:01:55,235
Now in some cases, the early stage
seed funding is often called

28
00:01:55,235 --> 00:01:57,352
seed funding
or early stage funding,

29
00:01:57,352 --> 00:02:02,012
but it's also sometimes called
AA, series AA.

30
00:02:04,686 --> 00:02:07,544
Usually, AA refers to the round

31
00:02:07,544 --> 00:02:10,601
where is no equity given
in the company,

32
00:02:10,601 --> 00:02:12,440
so there is no ownership

33
00:02:12,440 --> 00:02:13,831
or control of the company
given out,

34
00:02:13,831 --> 00:02:15,616
but there's some money raised.

35
00:02:16,155 --> 00:02:19,522
Now let's discuss
different types of financing.

36
00:02:19,522 --> 00:02:23,845
We are going to talk about
four different types of financing today.

37
00:02:23,845 --> 00:02:26,185
There are actually many more kinds

38
00:02:26,185 --> 00:02:29,303
but these are the main four
that you'll probably hear about

39
00:02:29,303 --> 00:02:31,068
and that you'll probably use.

40
00:02:31,068 --> 00:02:35,613
The first one is a gift or donation

41
00:02:36,343 --> 00:02:40,052
and that means that you are
receiving some money

42
00:02:40,052 --> 00:02:44,267
with no expectation that you are
going to give the money back.

43
00:02:45,167 --> 00:02:46,757
Then we have debt financing,

44
00:02:46,757 --> 00:02:49,882
where there is an expectation
that you're going to give the money back

45
00:02:49,882 --> 00:02:52,870
possibly, with an interest payment;

46
00:02:52,870 --> 00:02:54,310
so you'll give them more back

47
00:02:54,310 --> 00:02:56,581
than what you borrowed from the investors.

48
00:02:56,851 --> 00:02:59,320
And then, we have equity financing,

49
00:02:59,320 --> 00:03:02,207
which is basically,
an ownership share of the company.

50
00:03:03,197 --> 00:03:06,807
Finally, we're having convertible debt,

51
00:03:06,807 --> 00:03:10,829
which starts out as a loan and then,

52
00:03:10,829 --> 00:03:14,318
possibly converts to
an equity position in the company.

53
00:03:14,318 --> 00:03:16,475
So let's go through each and each
of these, one at a time,

54
00:03:16,475 --> 00:03:19,653
and talk about the pluses
and minuses of these different options.

55
00:03:19,653 --> 00:03:22,585
The first one is gifts or donations.

56
00:03:23,235 --> 00:03:27,933
And these are cash,
or in-kind contributions

57
00:03:28,213 --> 00:03:30,918
that someone provides
to the entrepreneur.

58
00:03:31,178 --> 00:03:35,972
They are given with no expectations
with getting anything in return,

59
00:03:35,972 --> 00:03:39,344
so it's really "free money",
if you think about it.

60
00:03:39,344 --> 00:03:41,470
Now why would you want
to have a gift or donation?

61
00:03:42,030 --> 00:03:45,250
It's clear that there is
no strings attached to this,

62
00:03:45,250 --> 00:03:46,562
there's no consideration.

63
00:03:46,562 --> 00:03:47,739
Consideration is when one party

64
00:03:47,739 --> 00:03:51,804
gives up something
to another party in exchange.

65
00:03:51,804 --> 00:03:54,945
So, in this case,
you're really just getting the money.

66
00:03:54,945 --> 00:03:58,978
The disadvantage of this approach

67
00:03:58,978 --> 00:04:02,899
is that it takes time to raise gifts.

68
00:04:03,389 --> 00:04:05,932
We've mentioned before
on one of the prior segments;

69
00:04:06,802 --> 00:04:09,508
raising money is not free.

70
00:04:10,008 --> 00:04:11,676
It takes time.

71
00:04:12,496 --> 00:04:14,710
It costs you something.

72
00:04:14,710 --> 00:04:16,192
And in this case,

73
00:04:16,192 --> 00:04:19,821
you are going to raise a lot of gifts
that can often be quite small,

74
00:04:19,821 --> 00:04:22,453
and you might spend up
spending a lot of time

75
00:04:22,453 --> 00:04:24,491
to raise this sort of money

76
00:04:24,491 --> 00:04:28,192
because it's hard to attract people
to give you gifts,

77
00:04:28,192 --> 00:04:29,980
unless you know them very, very well.

78
00:04:29,980 --> 00:04:32,792
The second type of financing
that we want to talk about today

79
00:04:32,792 --> 00:04:35,160
is debt financing.

80
00:04:35,160 --> 00:04:36,832
Now debt financing is

81
00:04:36,832 --> 00:04:43,082
when the entrepreneur promises
to pay back the money with interest.

82
00:04:46,102 --> 00:04:48,574
This is a loan, it's called a loan,

83
00:04:48,574 --> 00:04:50,898
and it occurs
for a certain amount of money.

84
00:04:50,898 --> 00:04:53,155
I am borrowing $10,000.

85
00:04:53,155 --> 00:04:55,124
I need to pay back $10,000.

86
00:04:55,124 --> 00:04:59,514
The loan itself is often called
a <i>note</i> or a <i>bond</i>.

87
00:05:00,114 --> 00:05:02,936
Bonds are not usually used
to start up companies,

88
00:05:02,936 --> 00:05:09,165
but a note refers
to the loan instrument itself.

89
00:05:10,654 --> 00:05:13,456
In many cases, with startup companies,

90
00:05:13,456 --> 00:05:15,004
the debt is not collateralized,

91
00:05:15,004 --> 00:05:17,543
in other words, it's an unsecured loan.

92
00:05:17,543 --> 00:05:19,134
They are lending you the money

93
00:05:19,134 --> 00:05:23,884
and you don't have any assets to sell off
in case you don't pay them back.

94
00:05:26,008 --> 00:05:29,403
Therefore, the borrower
has to pay interest,

95
00:05:29,403 --> 00:05:31,681
and the interest is predecided.

96
00:05:31,681 --> 00:05:34,207
Of course, some lenders,
like your family members

97
00:05:34,207 --> 00:05:37,083
may give you a loan with no interest.

98
00:05:37,873 --> 00:05:39,665
They want to get their principal back.

99
00:05:40,025 --> 00:05:43,341
But most investors will want
to receive interest;

100
00:05:43,341 --> 00:05:47,118
It's also called
the <i>coupon rate</i> of the loan.

101
00:05:49,299 --> 00:05:53,080
The loan usually has a fixed time
for repayment,

102
00:05:53,080 --> 00:05:55,294
one year, two years, five years,

103
00:05:55,294 --> 00:05:57,547
and that's called the <i>term of the loan</i>.

104
00:05:58,151 --> 00:06:00,376
The one thing that's interesting 
about the loan

105
00:06:00,376 --> 00:06:04,909
is that there is no ownership
or decision-making power inherent

106
00:06:04,909 --> 00:06:06,883
in debt financing in general.

107
00:06:07,085 --> 00:06:08,674
As long as you keep paying them back.

108
00:06:09,154 --> 00:06:11,907
If you don't pay your interest payments,

109
00:06:11,907 --> 00:06:14,681
in certain cases, the person
who's made the loan

110
00:06:14,681 --> 00:06:17,356
might be able to force you
into bankruptcy.

111
00:06:17,356 --> 00:06:23,500
But in general, they don't control
your strategy, your marketing decisions,

112
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:24,794
your product development.

113
00:06:24,794 --> 00:06:27,130
They don't have a say
in running your business.

114
00:06:27,720 --> 00:06:29,736
So, what are the advantages of doing

115
00:06:29,736 --> 00:06:31,868
this particular type of financing?

116
00:06:31,868 --> 00:06:33,492
First of all, it's very simple,

117
00:06:34,222 --> 00:06:39,517
and the entrepreneur gets to keep
the ownership and control of the company.

118
00:06:40,277 --> 00:06:43,363
The disadvantage
is that you don't gain much

119
00:06:43,363 --> 00:06:45,335
from interacting with the loan officer.

120
00:06:45,335 --> 00:06:48,010
You can't ask him for advice
on running your business.

121
00:06:48,010 --> 00:06:50,946
They are not experts in running a business.

122
00:06:52,466 --> 00:06:54,403
A huge disadvantage, of course,

123
00:06:54,403 --> 00:06:57,434
is that you need to keep generating cash.

124
00:06:57,434 --> 00:07:01,652
You need to keep paying back the loan
every period, whatever that is,

125
00:07:01,652 --> 00:07:04,267
maybe it's a monthly payment,
or a quarterly payment,

126
00:07:04,267 --> 00:07:06,171
but you need to keep paying that loan

127
00:07:06,171 --> 00:07:08,287
and it does eat up some cash.

128
00:07:09,347 --> 00:07:13,223
The third type of financing
is called <i>equity financing</i>.

129
00:07:13,223 --> 00:07:18,180
This is where the entrepreneur gives up
an ownership stake in the company.

130
00:07:19,628 --> 00:07:24,428
That means that the entrepreneur
is receiving some cash from the investor,

131
00:07:24,428 --> 00:07:26,480
and in return,

132
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:29,625
is selling a share of the company.

133
00:07:31,519 --> 00:07:36,224
And that means that the company
it is going to have a certain <i>valuation</i>.

134
00:07:38,244 --> 00:07:40,806
The definition of valuation is basically,

135
00:07:40,806 --> 00:07:45,360
the total expected value of all
of the future profits of the company

136
00:07:46,030 --> 00:07:50,462
brought back to the present dollar terms.

137
00:07:51,372 --> 00:07:55,491
For example, you might ask an investor

138
00:07:55,491 --> 00:07:57,461
to give you $100,000 dollars,

139
00:07:57,632 --> 00:08:01,057
and you are willing to give up
25% of your company

140
00:08:01,057 --> 00:08:02,895
to receive that $100,000 dollars.

141
00:08:03,711 --> 00:08:05,335
That makes your company worth

142
00:08:05,335 --> 00:08:08,636
$400,000 more or less post-money.

143
00:08:08,636 --> 00:08:11,262
We call it post-money because the $100,000

144
00:08:11,262 --> 00:08:14,043
is actually included in the $400,000

145
00:08:14,043 --> 00:08:17,024
making it for one quarter,

146
00:08:17,024 --> 00:08:19,146
in other words, a 25% of the company.

147
00:08:20,342 --> 00:08:24,366
That money put it in that valuation,
which is $400,000,

148
00:08:24,366 --> 00:08:25,805
would be brought forward,

149
00:08:25,805 --> 00:08:27,825
in future rounds,

150
00:08:28,285 --> 00:08:30,306
and depending on how things
change on the market

151
00:08:30,306 --> 00:08:32,552
that would be the basis of the valuation,

152
00:08:32,552 --> 00:08:34,936
that would be the pre-money valuation

153
00:08:34,936 --> 00:08:36,344
for the next round.

154
00:08:36,344 --> 00:08:37,275
If nothing changes.

155
00:08:37,275 --> 00:08:38,474
Now, of course, you might find out

156
00:08:38,474 --> 00:08:41,104
that the market is growing more rapidly
than you thought before

157
00:08:41,104 --> 00:08:45,320
which would make your pre-money valuation
grow in the interum.

158
00:08:46,580 --> 00:08:49,267
All of thee details,
this pre-money evaluation,

159
00:08:49,267 --> 00:08:50,851
how much you are expecting,

160
00:08:50,851 --> 00:08:53,501
how much of the company you are giving up,

161
00:08:53,951 --> 00:08:56,716
and how much the company
is worth afterwards

162
00:08:56,716 --> 00:09:00,022
are specified in what is called
a <i>term sheet</i>.

163
00:09:00,022 --> 00:09:02,607
This basically gives
the terms and conditions

164
00:09:02,607 --> 00:09:04,424
for the investment itself.

165
00:09:05,374 --> 00:09:08,266
Why would you want
to go through all of this

166
00:09:08,266 --> 00:09:11,510
to gain some investment in your company?

167
00:09:11,510 --> 00:09:15,360
The first issue is
that you can have a network

168
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:19,600
and you can have advice
from the people who make the investment.

169
00:09:19,600 --> 00:09:22,003
People often call this <i>smart money</i>,

170
00:09:22,003 --> 00:09:25,068
because that means the money
is coming in, plus you can get

171
00:09:25,068 --> 00:09:28,279
the advice or the network
from the investors.

172
00:09:28,279 --> 00:09:30,442
And another good reason for doing this

173
00:09:30,442 --> 00:09:34,168
is that this reduces the cash drain
on the company,

174
00:09:34,168 --> 00:09:35,988
since you don't need to pay the interest

175
00:09:35,988 --> 00:09:37,576
like you would in a loan,

176
00:09:37,576 --> 00:09:41,310
you can then be more flexible
with your business operations.

177
00:09:41,310 --> 00:09:44,242
Of course, the biggest disadvantage

178
00:09:44,242 --> 00:09:48,614
is the one I think maybe entrepreneurs
think about this a little too much,

179
00:09:48,614 --> 00:09:50,698
is that they have to share

180
00:09:50,698 --> 00:09:54,128
the ownership and control
of the company with the investor.

181
00:09:54,128 --> 00:09:57,716
That means that the entrepreneur
is no longer the sole owner,

182
00:09:57,716 --> 00:10:00,910
or the entrepreneur or the founders
and no longer the sole owners in the company

183
00:10:00,910 --> 00:10:02,859
but rather they are now sharing ownership

184
00:10:02,859 --> 00:10:05,076
in whatever percentage they agree upon

185
00:10:05,076 --> 00:10:06,934
with the investors.

186
00:10:06,934 --> 00:10:08,622
And some entrepreneurs are very nervous

187
00:10:08,622 --> 00:10:10,811
about giving up ownership and control.

188
00:10:10,811 --> 00:10:12,315
There might be some legal reasons too,

189
00:10:12,315 --> 00:10:15,320
legal protections
for the minority shareholders

190
00:10:15,320 --> 00:10:16,604
in this particular case

191
00:10:16,604 --> 00:10:20,753
which might also constrain
the ability of the entrepreneur

192
00:10:20,753 --> 00:10:24,202
to do whatever he or she wants to do.

193
00:10:25,203 --> 00:10:27,510
The last type of financing
that we want to talk about today

194
00:10:27,510 --> 00:10:31,405
is called <i>convertible debt</i>
or <i>convertible note</i>.

195
00:10:31,405 --> 00:10:33,761
Now, that is debt

196
00:10:33,921 --> 00:10:37,712
that can be converted
into equity later on.

197
00:10:37,712 --> 00:10:39,677
So, in the beginning stages

198
00:10:39,677 --> 00:10:43,728
the investment is treated
as any other loan

199
00:10:44,158 --> 00:10:47,530
and the investor receives
interest payments.

200
00:10:47,530 --> 00:10:50,526
However, at a certain point,

201
00:10:50,526 --> 00:10:54,395
which can be agreed upon
in the term sheet,

202
00:10:54,395 --> 00:10:56,509
the investor has the right

203
00:10:56,509 --> 00:10:59,330
to take the value of the debt

204
00:10:59,330 --> 00:11:02,243
and convert it into equity.

205
00:11:02,243 --> 00:11:03,690
Now when can they do this?

206
00:11:03,690 --> 00:11:05,580
This can be set up in the term sheet

207
00:11:05,580 --> 00:11:07,412
to be milestone-based

208
00:11:07,412 --> 00:11:09,453
or could be time-based.

209
00:11:09,453 --> 00:11:13,485
Of course, there needs to be
an equity round for this to happen,

210
00:11:13,485 --> 00:11:16,602
so that there is a valuation
of the company.

211
00:11:16,602 --> 00:11:19,055
But it could be when the first equity 
round is closing,

212
00:11:19,055 --> 00:11:20,872
it could be in the second one,

213
00:11:20,872 --> 00:11:22,202
it cold be other milestones

214
00:11:22,202 --> 00:11:24,943
when you've received
a certain amount of sales,

215
00:11:24,943 --> 00:11:28,163
when you've received a profitability,
reached profitability,

216
00:11:28,883 --> 00:11:30,722
or could be a time-based thing,

217
00:11:30,722 --> 00:11:32,800
like after one year or three years,

218
00:11:32,800 --> 00:11:36,920
if there is an equity round

219
00:11:36,920 --> 00:11:38,837
that creates a valuation of the company

220
00:11:38,837 --> 00:11:43,470
then we can convert the amount
that was invested in debt

221
00:11:43,470 --> 00:11:47,632
and convert it into a partial ownership
of the company.

222
00:11:48,252 --> 00:11:49,872
What's the conversion rate?

223
00:11:49,872 --> 00:11:51,952
It's a little bit trickier to explain,

224
00:11:52,507 --> 00:11:58,583
but basically, to entice the investor
to make this investment,

225
00:12:00,033 --> 00:12:05,915
you need to offer some sort
of cap, a valuation cap,

226
00:12:06,643 --> 00:12:09,778
on the valuation
of the company in the future.

227
00:12:10,678 --> 00:12:14,634
For example, if I were
to lend you $100,000,

228
00:12:15,667 --> 00:12:18,040
you might say to me, "Well, in the future

229
00:12:18,040 --> 00:12:22,070
if the company is worth
more than $1 million..."

230
00:12:22,070 --> 00:12:25,428
We will pretend
for this particular exercise

231
00:12:27,018 --> 00:12:29,236
that it's worth exactly $1 million,

232
00:12:29,236 --> 00:12:31,997
so you will end up
with 10% of the company.

233
00:12:32,111 --> 00:12:35,323
If it's worth $10 million,
you still get 10% of the company

234
00:12:35,323 --> 00:12:37,800
because your valuation is capped.

235
00:12:38,340 --> 00:12:40,189
Otherwise, the investor might think,

236
00:12:40,189 --> 00:12:42,860
"Well, I could put in $100,000 now,

237
00:12:42,860 --> 00:12:44,578
but if this company really takes off

238
00:12:44,578 --> 00:12:46,601
- which is what everyone wants -

239
00:12:46,601 --> 00:12:50,683
then I am going to be left
with only 1% of this company,

240
00:12:50,683 --> 00:12:53,203
even if I took a big, big risk
lending them this money

241
00:12:53,203 --> 00:12:54,703
in the early stages."

242
00:12:54,703 --> 00:12:57,461
That's why these valuation caps

243
00:12:57,461 --> 00:13:00,160
are set up as a bonus,

244
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:02,851
or as an enticement to the investors.

245
00:13:03,183 --> 00:13:06,076
So, why would you want
to do this kind of financing?

246
00:13:06,076 --> 00:13:08,609
It's becoming more and more common,

247
00:13:08,609 --> 00:13:12,356
there is definitely a trend
toward convertible debt.

248
00:13:13,806 --> 00:13:17,433
It can be quicker to negotiate
than an equity investment.

249
00:13:17,623 --> 00:13:22,109
And it definitely delays
the valuation discussion.

250
00:13:22,109 --> 00:13:25,138
Some entrepreneurs don't want
