00:27:13,013 --> 00:27:15,339
and an investor from a strategic partner,

499
00:27:16,539 --> 00:27:21,282
and the big company
could eventually acquire

500
00:27:21,282 --> 00:27:23,190
the startup company.

501
00:27:24,660 --> 00:27:26,974
From the startup's point of view
that's called the trade sale.

502
00:27:26,974 --> 00:27:29,691
Sell the whole company
to another company.

503
00:27:30,961 --> 00:27:32,444
Another option is

504
00:27:33,324 --> 00:27:38,569
the company can offer some percentage
of their shares to the public

505
00:27:39,584 --> 00:27:43,414
and this is the IPO
or the Initial Public Offering.

506
00:27:44,014 --> 00:27:46,952
This is done to raise
large amounts of money

507
00:27:46,952 --> 00:27:48,651
in the public capital market.

508
00:27:48,651 --> 00:27:51,137
There are a lot of legal implications,

509
00:27:52,137 --> 00:27:54,850
the founders often become
the minority shareholders

510
00:27:54,850 --> 00:28:01,910
and there is a legal framework
for how to govern the company

511
00:28:02,566 --> 00:28:04,382
after the IPO is done,

512
00:28:04,382 --> 00:28:07,931
but it does have the advantage of raising
a large amount of capital

513
00:28:07,931 --> 00:28:11,850
so that, in case there needs to be
some major investments made

514
00:28:11,850 --> 00:28:14,121
or some big marketing expenses

515
00:28:14,121 --> 00:28:16,248
or other sorts of capital expenditures

516
00:28:16,248 --> 00:28:21,305
then, that would be a natural way
to go to raise the money.

517
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:23,920
The third way is a management buyout

518
00:28:23,920 --> 00:28:26,447
and this is less common 
in a small company,

519
00:28:27,327 --> 00:28:30,571
but it could be
that the managers themselves,

520
00:28:30,571 --> 00:28:32,567
the managers, executives, founders,

521
00:28:32,567 --> 00:28:36,654
would turn around and buy the company back

522
00:28:37,444 --> 00:28:39,494
from the other investors.

523
00:28:40,726 --> 00:28:42,813
And you've probably heard
of a <i>leverage buyout</i>

524
00:28:42,813 --> 00:28:44,123
and in a leverage buyout

525
00:28:44,123 --> 00:28:48,756
is where the managers borrow money
to make this transaction.

